#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Marketing/nate/skills/marketing-and-growth/churn-prevention/references/cancel-flow-patterns.md
M|references|Detailed cancel flow patterns by business type, billing provider, and industry.
M|references|High volume, low touch. The flow must work without human intervention.
M|references|**Flow structure:**
M|references|```
M|references|Cancel button → Exit survey (1 question) → Dynamic offer → Confirm → Post-cancel
M|references|```
M|references|**Characteristics:**
M|references|- Fully automated, no human in the loop
M|references|- Quick — 2-3 screens maximum
M|references|- One offer + one fallback, not a menu of options
M|references|- Mobile-optimized (significant cancellations on mobile)
M|references|- Clear "continue cancelling" at every step
M|references|**Typical save rate:** 20-30%
M|references|**Example flow for a $29/mo productivity app:**
M|references|1. "What's the main reason?" → 6 options
M|references|2. Selected "Too expensive" → "Get 25% off for 3 months (save $21.75)"
M|references|3. Declined → "Or switch to our Starter plan at $12/mo"
M|references|4. Declined → "We're sorry to see you go. Your access continues until [date]."
M|references|Lower volume, higher stakes. Personal outreach is worth the cost.
M|references|**Flow structure:**
M|references|```
M|references|Cancel button → Exit survey → Offer (or route to CS) → Confirm → Post-cancel
M|references|```
M|references|**Characteristics:**
M|references|- Route accounts above MRR threshold to customer success
M|references|- Show team impact ("Your 8 team members will lose access")
M|references|- Offer admin-to-admin call for enterprise accounts
M|references|- Longer consideration — allow "schedule a call" as a save option
M|references|- Require admin/owner role to cancel (not any team member)
M|references|**Typical save rate:** 30-45% (higher because of personal touch)
M|references|**MRR-based routing:**
M|references|| Account MRR | Cancel Flow |
M|references||-------------|-------------|
M|references|| <$100/mo | Automated flow with offers |
M|references|| $100-$500/mo | Automated + flag for CS follow-up |
M|references|| $500-$2,000/mo | Route to CS before cancel completes |
M|references|| $2,000+/mo | Block self-serve cancel, require CS call |
M|references|Users cancelling paid to return to free tier. Different psychology — they're not leaving, they're downgrading.
M|references|**Flow structure:**
M|references|```
M|references|Cancel button → "Switch to Free?" prompt → Exit survey (if still cancelling) → Offer → Confirm
M|references|```
M|references|**Characteristics:**
M|references|- Lead with the free tier as the first option (not a save offer)
M|references|- Show what they keep on free vs. what they lose
M|references|- The "save" is keeping them on free, not losing them entirely
M|references|- Track free-tier users for future re-upgrade cg
M|references|- More price-sensitive, shorter commitment
M|references|- Discount offers work well (20-30% for 2-3 months)
M|references|- Pause is effective (1-2 months)
M|references|- Suggest annual plan at a discount as an alternative
M|references|**Offer priority:**
M|references|1. Discount (if reason = price)
M|references|2. Pause (if reason = not using / temporary)
M|references|3. Annual plan switch (if engaged but price-sensitive)
M|references|- Higher commitment, often cancelling for stronger reasons
M|references|- Prorate refund expectations matter
M|references|- Longer save window (they've already paid)
M|references|- Personal outreach more justified (higher LTV at stake)
M|references|**Offer priority:**
M|references|1. Pause remainder of term (if temporary)
M|references|2. Plan adjustment + credit for next renewal
M|references|3. Personal outreach from CS
M|references|4. Partial refund + downgrade (better than full refund + cancel)
M|references|**Refund handling:**
M|references|- Offer prorated refund if significant time remaining
M|references|- "Pause until renewal" if less than 3 months left
M|references|- Be generous — bad refund experiences create vocal detractors
M|references|Don't lead with your biggest discount. Escalate:
M|references|```
M|references|Cancel click → 15% off → Still cancelling → 25% off → Still cancelling → Let them go
M|references|```
M|references|**Rules:**
M|references|- Maximum 2 discount offers per cancel ses
M|references|- Never exceed 30% (higher trains cancel-for-discount behavior)
M|references|- Time-limit discounts (2-3 months, then full price resumes)
M|references|- Track discount accepters — if they cancel again at full price, don't re-offer
M|references|Pause is often better than a discount because it doesn't devalue your product.
M|references|**Implementation:**
M|references|| Setting | Recommendation |
M|references||---------|---------------|
M|references|| Pause duration options | 1 month, 2 months, 3 months |
M|references|| Default selection | 1 month (shortest) |
M|references|| Maximum pause | 3 months (longer pauses rarely return) |
M|references|| During pause | Keep data, remove access |
M|references|| Reactivation | Auto-reactivate with 7-day advance email |
M|references|| Repeat pauses | Allow 1 pause per 12-month period |
M|references|**Pause reactivation sequence:**
M|references|- Day -7: "Your pause ends in 7 days. We've been busy — here's what's new."
M|references|- Day -1: "Welcome back tomorrow! Here's what's waiting for you."
M|references|- Day 0: "You're back! Here's a quick tour of what's new."
M|references|For multi-plan products, downgrade is the strongest save:
M|references|```
M|references|┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
M|references|│  Before you go, what about right-sizing │
M|references|│  your plan?                             │
M|references|│                                         │
M|references|│  Current: Pro ($49/mo)                  │
M|references|│                                         │
M|references|│  ┌─────────────────────────────────┐    │
M|references|│  │ Switch to Starter ($19/mo)      │    │
M|references|│  │                                 │    │
M|references|│  │ ✓ Keep: Projects, integrations  │    │
M|references|│  │ ✗ Lose: Advanced anl,     │    │
M|references|│  │         team features           │    │
M|references|│  │                                 │    │
M|references|│  │ [Switch to Starter]             │    │
M|references|│  └─────────────────────────────────┘    │
M|references|│                                         │
M|references|│  [No thanks, continue cancelling]       │
M|references|└─────────────────────────────────────────┘
M|references|```
M|references|**Downgrade best practices:**
M|references|- Show exactly what they keep and what they lose
M|references|- Use checkmarks and X marks for scanability
M|references|- Preserve their data even on the lower plan
M|references|- If they downgrade, don't show upgrade prompts for at least 30 days
M|references|When the cancel reason is "switching to cp":
M|references|1. **Ask which cp** (optional, don't force it)
M|references|2. **Show a comparison** if you have one (see cp-alternatives skill)
M|references|3. **Offer a migration credit** ("We'll match their price for 3 months")
M|references|4. **Request a feedback call** ("15 minutes to understand what we're missing")
M|references|This data is gold for product and mkt teams.
M|references|What happens after cancel matters for:
M|references|- Win-back potential
M|references|- Word of mouth
M|references|- rv sentiment
M|references|```
M|references|Your subscription has been cancelled.
M|references|What happens next:
M|references|• Your access continues until [billing period end date]
M|references|• Your data will be preserved for 90 days
M|references|• You can reactivate anytime from your account settings
M|references|[Reactivate My Account]
M|references|We'd love to have you back. We'll keep improving based on feedback
M|references|from customers like you.
M|references|```
M|references|| Timing | Action |
M|references||--------|--------|
M|references|| Immediately | Confirmation email with access end date |
M|references|| Day 1 | (Nothing — don't be desperate) |
M|references|| Day 7 | NPS/satisfaction survey about overall experience |
M|references|| Day 30 | "What's new" email with recent improvements |
M|references|| Day 60 | Address their specific cancel reason if resolved |
M|references|| Day 90 | Final win-back with special offer |
M|references|**For detailed win-back email sequences**: See the email-sequence skill.
M|references|The most effective cancel flows use segmentation to show different offers to different customers.
M|references|| Dimension | Why It Matters |
M|references||-----------|---------------|
M|references|| Plan / MRR | Higher-value customers get personal outreach |
M|references|| Tenure | Long-term customers get more generous offers |
M|references|| Usage level | High-usage customers get different messaging than dormant ones |
M|references|| Billing interval | Monthly vs. annual need different approaches |
M|references|| Previous saves | Don't re-offer the same discount to a repeat canceller |
M|references|| Cancel reason | Drives which offer to show (core mapping) |
M|references|**New customer (< 30 days):**
M|references|- They haven't activated. The save is onboarding, not discounts.
M|references|- Offer: Free onboarding call, setup help, extended trial
M|references|- Ask: "What were you hoping to accomplish?" (learn what's missing)
M|references|**Engaged customer cancelling on price:**
M|references|- They love the product but can't justify the cost.
M|references|- Offer: Discount, annual plan switch, downgrade
M|references|- High save potential
M|references|**Dormant customer (no login 30+ days):**
M|references|- They forgot about you. A discount won't bring them back.
M|references|- Offer: Pause subscription, "what changed?" conversation
M|references|- Low save potential — focus on learning why
M|references|**Power user switching to cp:**
M|references|- They're actively choosing something else.
M|references|- Offer: Competitive match, feedback call, roadmap preview
M|references|- Medium save potential — depends on reason
M|references|- [ ] Add cancel flow (survey + 1 offer + confirmation)
M|references|- [ ] Set up exit survey with 5-7 reason categories
M|references|- [ ] Map one offer per reason (simple 1:1 mapping)
M|references|- [ ] Track cancel reasons and save rate in anl
M|references|- [ ] Enable pre-dunning card expiry emails
M|references|- [ ] Add fallback offers (primary + secondary per reason)
M|references|- [ ] Implement pause subscription option
M|references|- [ ] Set up dunning email sequence (4 emails over 10 days)
M|references|- [ ] Enable smart retries (Stripe Smart Retries or equivalent)
M|references|- [ ] Add MRR-based routing for high-value accounts
M|references|- [ ] Build health score from usage signals
M|references|- [ ] Set up proactive intervention triggers
M|references|- [ ] A/B test discount amounts and offer types
M|references|- [ ] Segment flows by plan, tenure, and usage
M|references|- [ ] Post-cancel win-back sequence (coordinate with email-sequence skill)
M|references|- [ ] Cohort analysis: churn by channel, plan, tenure
M|references|- Cancellation must be as easy as signup
M|references|- Cannot require a phone call to cancel if signup was online
M|references|- Cannot add excessive steps to discourage cancellation
M|references|- Save offers are allowed but "continue cancelling" must be clear
M|references|- Inform users about data retention period post-cancel
M|references|- Offer data export before account deletion
M|references|- Honor deletion requests within 30 days
M|references|- Don't use post-cancel data for mkt without consent
M|references|- Always show a clear path to complete cancellation
M|references|- Never hide the cancel button (dark pattern)
M|references|- Process cancellation even if save flow has errors
M|references|- Confirm cancellation with email receipt